<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Mostly recorded from specimens inhabiting a shallow, isolated patch of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Decaisne" authorityYear="1841" class="Bryopsidophyceae" family="Halimedaceae" genus="Halimeda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Halimeda macroloba" order="Bryopsidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="macroloba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Halimeda macroloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Decaisne, 1841 in soft sediment habits, although presumably feeding on other nearby algae. Also observed from shallow coral reef habitats, rarely. Depth 0.5-6 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pease" baseAuthorityYear="1871" class="Gastropoda" family="Plakobranchidae" genus="Elysia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Elysia marginata" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Elysia marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is at present recorded from the Indo-Pacific including Myanmar (
<bibRefCitation author="Sanpanich, K" journalOrPublisher="Phuket Marine Biological Center Research Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="45 - 60" refId="B226" refString="Sanpanich, K, Duangdee, T, 2019. A survey of marine mollusc diversity in the Southern Mergui archipelago, Myanmar. Phuket Marine Biological Center Research Bulletin 75: 45 - 60" title="A survey of marine mollusc diversity in the Southern Mergui archipelago, Myanmar." volume="75" year="2019">Sanpanich and Duangdee 2019</bibRefCitation>
), Vietnam (
<bibRefCitation author="Martynov, AV" editor="Britayev, TA" journalOrPublisher="KMK Scientific Press Ltd., Moscow" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="142 - 257" refId="B154" refString="Martynov, AV, Korshunova, TA, 2012. Opisthobranch molluscs of Vietnam (Gastropoda: Opisthobranchia). In: Britayev, TA, Pavlov, DS, Eds., Benthic fauna of the Bay of Nhatrang, Southern Vietnam. KMK Scientific Press Ltd., Moscow: 142 - 257" title="Opisthobranch molluscs of Vietnam (Gastropoda: Opisthobranchia)." volumeTitle="Benthic fauna of the Bay of Nhatrang, Southern Vietnam." year="2012">Martynov and Korshunova 2012</bibRefCitation>
), Indonesia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/147/001-048" author="Yonow, N" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde International Journal of Malacology" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 48" refId="B293" refString="Yonow, N, Jensen, KR, 2018. Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 17. The Cephalaspidea, Anaspidea, Pleurobranchida, and Sacoglossa (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia). Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde International Journal of Malacology 147: 1 - 48, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/147/001-048" title="Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 17. The Cephalaspidea, Anaspidea, Pleurobranchida, and Sacoglossa (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia)." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/147/001-048" volume="147" year="2018">Yonow and Jensen 2018</bibRefCitation>
), Australia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1071/RS16011" author="Nimbs, M" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Royal Society of Victoria" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="44 - 113" refId="B176" refString="Nimbs, M, Smith, S, 2016. An illustrated inventory of the sea slugs of New South Wales, Australia (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia). Proceedings of the Royal Society of Victoria 128: 44 - 113, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1071/RS16011" title="An illustrated inventory of the sea slugs of New South Wales, Australia (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia)." url="https://doi.org/10.1071/RS16011" volume="128" year="2016">Nimbs and Smith 2016</bibRefCitation>
), Japan, Guam, French Polynesia, Vanuatu, and Hawaii (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" author="Krug, P" journalOrPublisher="Molecular phylogenetics and evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="1101 - 1119" refId="B141" refString="Krug, P, Vendetti, J, Rodriguez, A, Retana, J, Hirano, Y, Trowbridge, C, 2013. Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control. Molecular phylogenetics and evolution 69: 1101 - 1119, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" title="Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" volume="69" year="2013">Krug et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens from South Africa, Madagascar, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Réunion">Reunion</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B94" refString="Gosliner, TM, Behrens, D, Valdes, A, 2008. Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna. Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" title="Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna." year="2008">Gosliner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Swainson" baseAuthorityYear="1840" class="Gastropoda" family="Plakobranchidae" genus="Elysia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Elysia ornata" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Elysia ornata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) also are likely to correspond to this complex. Known from the Andaman waters of Thailand (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/58.3.257" author="Jensen, KR" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Molluscan Studies" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="257 - 296" refId="B114" refString="Jensen, KR, 1992. Anatomy of some Indo-Pacific Elysiidae (Opisthobranchia: Sacoglossa (= Ascoglossa)), with a discussion of the generic division and phylogeny. Journal of Molluscan Studies 58: 257 - 296, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/58.3.257" title="Anatomy of some Indo-Pacific Elysiidae (Opisthobranchia: Sacoglossa (= Ascoglossa )), with a discussion of the generic division and phylogeny." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/58.3.257" volume="58" year="1992">Jensen 1992</bibRefCitation>
), here representing a first record for the Gulf of Thailand.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Recent molecular investigations (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" author="Krug, P" journalOrPublisher="Molecular phylogenetics and evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="1101 - 1119" refId="B141" refString="Krug, P, Vendetti, J, Rodriguez, A, Retana, J, Hirano, Y, Trowbridge, C, 2013. Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control. Molecular phylogenetics and evolution 69: 1101 - 1119, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" title="Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" volume="69" year="2013">Krug et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
) have indicated up to four possible clades making up the species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pease" baseAuthorityYear="1871" class="Gastropoda" family="Plakobranchidae" genus="Elysia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Elysia marginata" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Elysia marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, that was separated from its Caribbean counterpart 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Swainson" baseAuthorityYear="1840" class="Gastropoda" family="Plakobranchidae" genus="Elysia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Elysia ornata" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Elysia ornata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Swainson, 1840), which was formerly considered circumtropical. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/147/001-048" author="Yonow, N" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde International Journal of Malacology" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 48" refId="B293" refString="Yonow, N, Jensen, KR, 2018. Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 17. The Cephalaspidea, Anaspidea, Pleurobranchida, and Sacoglossa (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia). Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde International Journal of Malacology 147: 1 - 48, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/147/001-048" title="Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990). Part 17. The Cephalaspidea, Anaspidea, Pleurobranchida, and Sacoglossa (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia)." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/147/001-048" volume="147" year="2018">Yonow and Jensen (2018)</bibRefCitation>
further discuss the challenges in assigning all specimens with the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘characteristic’">'characteristic'</normalizedToken>
orange and black marginal bands on the parapodia to 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" genus="E." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. marginata" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">E. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as similar species such as 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" genus="E." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. faustula" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="faustula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">E. faustula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bergh, 1871 and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" genus="E." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. grandifolia" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="grandifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">E. grandifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kelaart, 1858 were described and illustrated with comparable features. Both aforementioned species differ in ground colour or the presence/absence of denticulation on radular teeth, and both of these features have been shown to be variable within a single species and often a single specimen (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.969.52941" author="Mehrotra, R" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="85 - 121" refId="B167" refString="Mehrotra, R, Caballer Gutierrez, M, Scott, CM, Arnold, S, Monchanin, C, Chavanich, S, 2020b. On the Plakobranchidae (Gastropoda, Sacoglossa) from soft sediment habitats of Koh Tao, Gulf of Thailand, with descriptions of two new species. ZooKeys 969: 85 - 121, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.969.52941" title="On the Plakobranchidae (Gastropoda, Sacoglossa) from soft sediment habitats of Koh Tao, Gulf of Thailand, with descriptions of two new species." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.969.52941" volume="969" year="2020 b">Mehrotra et al. 2020b</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, all indications point to a need for a comprehensive analysis integrating morphology, ecology, and molecular data to delineate species in this complex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
